Understanding View Manager Status Classifications

Many View Manager status classifications have names that are similar to those StarTeam uses to indicate the relationship between a file's tip revision in the repository and the working file on your workstation. However, the status classifications shown in View Manager have nothing to do with working files. Instead, they compare tip revisions of corresponding files, and the files to which they refer may be located in the same or different repositories.

In many cases, a View Manager status suggests a number of possible actions, each with its own result.

If you have StarTeam open while you perform an View Manager operation, be aware that the status of your working files will change if their corresponding tip revisions change.

View Manager Status Classifications

Status: Current. Corresponding files exist and have not changed since the last run operation or last recorded merge.
Action: No action.
Result: No action taken.

 

Status: Merge. File has changed in both source and target.
Action: Manual merge. Resolution of conflicts or all differences in test files must be manual and use the specified merge utility. For binary files, you might want to compare the two files in the application in which they were created.
Result: Manual merge needed.

Action: Automatic merge. An automatic merge is possible because the corresponding text files have no conflicts. The merged file was checked in to the target and/or source, depending on the operation and the contents of the merged file.
Result: Merged.

Action: Use source file.
Result: Source file checked into target.

Action: Use target file.
Result: Target file checked into source.

 

Status: Missing From Target. Object exists only in the source.
Action: Add to target (determined by options settings).
Result: Added.

Action: Delete from source (determined by option settings).
Result: Deleted.

Action: Move from source to target (determined by option settings).
Result: Moved. Deleted from the source and added to the target.

Action: No action.
Result: Shared from parent in source.

 

Status: Modified. File has changed in target only.
Action: No action. Bidirectional synchronization was not specified.
Result: No action taken.

Action: Use target file. Target file is to be used for text or binary file resolution in bidirectional synchronization.
Result: Target file checked in to source.

 

Status: Not In Source. Object exists only in the target.
Action: Add to source (determined by object settings).
Result: Added.

Action: Delete from target (determined by object settings).
Result: Deleted.

Action: Move from target to source (determined by object settings).
Result: Moved. Object was deleted from the target and added to the source.

Action: No action.
Result: Shared from parent in target.

 

Status: Out Of Date. The file has changed only in the source.
Action: Use source file.
Result: Source-to-target synchronization checked the source file into the target.

Action: No action. Synchronization other than source-to-target was specified.
Result: No action taken.

 

Status: Exists In Both. Although a file exists in both the source and target, this is a missing-objects-only synchronization.
Action: No action. A missing-objects-only synchronization ignores files that exist in both the source and the target.
Result: No action taken.

 

Status: Exists In Both. A server, project, view, or folder exists in both the source and target. Neither the option settings nor the run operation requires any action to be taken on this object.
Action: Check children for possible actions.
Result: Checking done.

 

Status: Equivalent Name. When the source object is the same type as the target object and a synchronization is specified as the run type, two objects can be considered equivalent, even if their names are different. If the objects are views, their root folders are equivalent.
Action: Check children for possible actions.
Result: Checking done.

 

Status: Unknown. Corresponding files exists in the source and the target but appear to be unrelated.
Action: No action. View Manager cannot determine what action should be performed.

Result: No action performed. View Manager cannot determine what action should be performed.

 

Status: <any status>
Action: <any action to be taken>
Result: Check-in failed. File could not be checked in. For example, it may have been locked.

 

Status: Previously processed. In a restarted operation, an object has this status if it was processed in a previous attempt to perform the operation.
Action: No action.
Result: No action taken.
